comment: I hate to tell you this but I am also a lawyer and specialise in DA. I was originally (30 years ago) trained as a sex crimes prosecutor. In both types of cases, the main problem for us as well as the cops is the fear of the victims to tell what happened. These bodycam videos don't PROVE anything legally. These types of scenarios aren't like , say, a murder scene where the cops might locate a weapon or blood splatter or even a dead body. I have known innumerable cases where friends or family will call the cops and the victim will cover for the abuser. I am not saying this is the case here. We do not know anything. They will clean up after a destructive attack in the home, they will mend broken windows and doors... Again, I am not taking sides between these two but hoping to educate people about the complexity of these cases. My mother spent her career as a Trauma specialist in a Level 1 Trauma Unit in Harlem, NYC. She has dealt with violence of every variety, including domestic and sexual. She often described women coming in with a broken jaw AGAIN, for the 4th or 5th time in some cases, and saying she fell. Plus, the combination of alcohol and abuse is like the perfect cocktail, so to speak. I'd say this was a very dysfunctional relationship wherein the abuse is often emotional and psychological in the main. We do not know and the best thing is to ease off the gossip fest and let the matter be addressed appropriately. BTW, lawyers can be like pouring gas on a fire and often push their clients to make allegations that are specious in order to get leverage. I don't doubt JD especially has been viewed by divorce lawyers as fat pockets and it is they who make the benefit from this sort of internet 'case making'. One last thing, marrying a woman so much younger (or vice versa) does tend to end dysfunctionally because both people are psychologically and experientially at such enormously different stages in life. He is 57, she is 20-something. It's like having a child in a way. I'm not yet 57 but I have a 24 year old son and there is NO WAY I'd dream of getting involved, or marrying, one of his friends. It's not an age bias since I did have relationships with older men, which can be good for a young woman but at some stage I always realised it was time to move on, on my own track to growing in ways they had already done. I learned a lot but was less emotionally settled as I am now. Let's just wish them both peace and ourselves as well. Cheers.
